# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baking-powder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Abel Boyer was probably born on 24 June 1667 at Castres, in Upper Languedoc, southern France.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] His father, Pierre Boyer, one of the two consuls or chief magistrates of Castres, had been suspended and fined for his Protestantism.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Boyer's education at the academy of Puylaurens was interrupted by the religious disturbances, and leaving France with his maternal uncle Pierre Campdomerc, a noted Huguenot preacher, he finished his studies at Franeker in Friesland, after a brief episode, it is said, of military service in Holland.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Proceeding to England in 1689 he fell into great poverty, and is represented as transcribing and preparing for the press Dr.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Thomas Smith's edition of William Camden's Latin correspondence (London, 1691).
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] A good classical scholar, Boyer became in 1692 tutor to Allen Bathurst, afterwards first Earl Bathurst, whose father Sir Benjamin was treasurer of the household of the princess, afterwards Queen Anne.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Probably through this connection he was appointed French teacher to her son Prince William, Duke of Gloucester, for whose use he prepared and to whom he dedicated *The Complete French Master*, published in 1694.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Disappointed of advancement on account of his zeal for Whig principles, he abandoned tuition for authorship.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] In December 1699, Boyer produced on the London stage, with indifferent success, a modified translation in blank verse of Jean Racine's *Iphigénie*, which was published in 1700 as *Achilles or Iphigenia in Aulis, a tragedy written by Mr.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] A second edition of it appeared in 1714 as *The Victim, or Achilles and Iphigenia in Aulis*, in an "advertisement" prefixed to which Boyer stated that in its first form it had "passed the correction and approbation" of John Dryden.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] In 1699 also the work for which Boyer is best known was published, *The Royal Dictionary*, "In two parts.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Secondly, English and French", ostensibly composed for the use of the Duke of Gloucester, then dead.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] In 1700 Boyer produced an abridged version, and in 1702 a version titled in French was published in The Hague.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] It was much superior to every previous work of the kind, and has been the basis of very many subsequent French-English dictionaries; the last English unabridged edition is that of 1816; the edition published at Paris in 1860 is stated to be the 41st.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] For the English-French section Boyer claimed the merit of containing a more complete English dictionary than any previous one, the English words and idioms in it being defined and explained as well as accompanied by their French equivalents.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] The macrostructure and microstructure of the entries in Boyer's Royal Dictionary was copied by Ó Beaglaoich in his English-Irish Dictionary of 1732.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Among the English versions of French works executed in whole or in part by Boyer was a popular translation of Fénelon's *Télémaque*, of which a twelfth edition appeared in 1728.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Its contents, which were those of a monthly newspaper, included abstracts of the chief political pamphlets published on both sides, and, like the *Annals*, is, both from its form and matter, very useful for reference.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] *The Political State* is, moreover, particularly noticeable as being the first periodical, issued at brief intervals, which contained a parliamentary chronicle, and in which parliamentary debates were reported with comparative regularity and with some approximation to accuracy.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] In the case of the House of Lords' reports various devices, such as giving only the initials of the names of the speakers, were resorted to escape punishment, but in the case of the House of Commons the entire names were frequently given.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] The threat induced him to discontinue the publication of the debates.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] He intended to resume the work, but failed to carry out his intention.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] He died in a house which he had built for himself at Chelsea, London.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Besides conducting the periodicals mentioned, Boyer began in 1705 to edit the *Post-boy*, a thrice-a-week London news-sheet.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] His connection with it ended in August 1709, through a quarrel with the proprietor, when Boyer started on his own account a *True Post-boy*, which seems to have been short-lived.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] A *Case* which he printed in vindication of his right to use the name of *Post-boy* for his new venture gives some curious particulars of the way in which the news-sheets of the time were manufactured.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Boyer was discharged from custody through the intervention, he says, of Robert Harley, to whom he boasts of having rendered services.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Though he professed a strict political impartiality in the conduct of his principal periodicals, Boyer was a zealous whig.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] For this reason doubtless Alexander Pope gave him a niche in *The Dunciad* (book ii.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Boyer was a prolific author: the British Library's 1880 catalogue used nearly four folio pages of print to list his works.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] Boyer’s historical compilations were revisited by later historians.
[src:baking-powder/abel-boyer] In 1744–46, James Ralph’s *The History of England, During the Reigns of King William, Queen Anne, and King George I* criticised the derivative nature of some of Boyer’s work, grouping him with Burnet, Tindal, Kennett, and Oldmixon.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:baking-powder/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In chemistry, an **acid–base reaction** is a chemical reaction that occurs between an acid and a base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] It can be used to determine pH via titration.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Several theoretical frameworks provide alternative conceptions of the reaction mechanisms and their application in solving related problems; these are called the acid–base theories, for example, Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Their importance becomes apparent in analyzing acid–base reactions for gaseous or liquid species, or when acid or base character may be somewhat less apparent.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The first of these concepts was provided by the French chemist Antoine Lavoisier, around 1776.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] It is important to think of the acid–base reaction models as theories that complement each other.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] For example, the current Lewis model has the broadest definition of what an acid and base are, with the Brønsted–Lowry theory being a subset of what acids and bases are, and the Arrhenius theory being the most restrictive.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius theory describes an acid as a substance that increases the concentration of hydrogen ions (H3O+ or H+) in a solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] A base is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide ions (OH-) in a solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] However, Arrhenius's definition only applies to substances that are in water.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The concept of an acid–base reaction was first proposed in 1754 by Guillaume-François Rouelle, who introduced the word "base" into chemistry to mean a substance which reacts with an acid to give it solid form (as a salt).
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The first scientific concept of acids and bases was provided by Lavoisier in around 1776.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Lavoisier definition held for over 30 years, until the 1810 article and subsequent lectures by Sir Humphry Davy in which he proved the lack of oxygen in hydrogen sulfide (H2S), hydrogen telluride (H2Te), and the hydrohalic acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] However, Davy failed to develop a new theory, concluding that "acidity does not depend upon any particular elementary substance, but upon peculiar arrangement of various substances".
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] One notable modification of oxygen theory was provided by Jöns Jacob Berzelius, who stated that acids are oxides of nonmetals while bases are oxides of metals.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In 1838, Justus von Liebig proposed that an acid is a hydrogen-containing compound whose hydrogen can be replaced by a metal.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This redefinition was based on his extensive work on the chemical composition of organic acids, finishing the doctrinal shift from oxygen-based acids to hydrogen-based acids started by Davy.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Liebig's definition, while completely empirical, remained in use for almost 50 years until the adoption of the Arrhenius definition.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The first modern definition of acids and bases in molecular terms was devised by Svante Arrhenius.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] A hydrogen theory of acids, it followed from his 1884 work with Friedrich Wilhelm Ostwald in establishing the presence of ions in aqueous solution and led to Arrhenius receiving the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1903.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This causes the protonation of water, or the creation of the hydronium (H3O+) ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in modern times, the symbol H+ is interpreted as a shorthand for H3O+, because it is now known that a bare proton does not exist as a free species in aqueous solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This is the species which is measured by pH indicators to measure the acidity or basicity of a solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Arrhenius definitions of acidity and alkalinity are restricted to aqueous solutions and are not valid for most non-aqueous solutions, and refer to the concentration of the solvent ions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Under this definition, pure H2SO4 and HCl dissolved in toluene are not acidic, and molten NaOH and solutions of calcium amide in liquid ammonia are not alkaline.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This led to the development of the Brønsted–Lowry theory and subsequent Lewis theory to account for these non-aqueous exceptions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of an acid with a base is called a neutralization reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In this traditional representation an acid–base neutralization reaction is formulated as a double-replacement reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The modifier (aq) in this equation was implied by Arrhenius, rather than included explicitly.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] It indicates that the substances are dissolved in water.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Though all three substances, HCl, NaOH and NaCl are capable of existing as pure compounds, in aqueous solutions they are fully dissociated into the aquated ions H+, Cl−, Na+ and OH−.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is used to cause the dough for breads and cakes to "rise" by creating millions of tiny carbon dioxide bubbles.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is not to be confused with baking soda, which is sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3).
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Baking powder is a mixture of baking soda (sodium bicarbonate) and acidic salts.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The bubbles are created because, when the baking powder is combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Whether commercially or domestically prepared, the principles behind baking powder formulations remain the same.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The real reactions are more complicated because the acids are complicated.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] A typical formulation (by weight) could call for 30% sodium bicarbonate, 5–12% monocalcium phosphate, and 21–26% sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Alternately, a commercial baking powder might use sodium acid pyrophosphate as one of the two acidic components instead of sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Another typical acid in such formulations is cream of tartar (KC4H5O6), a derivative of tartaric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] An acid–base reaction is, thus, the removal of a proton from the acid and its addition to the base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The removal of a proton from an acid produces its *conjugate base*, which is the acid with a proton removed.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The reception of a proton by a base produces its *conjugate acid*, which is the base with a proton added.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Unlike the previous definitions, the Brønsted–Lowry definition does not refer to the formation of salt and solvent, but instead to the formation of *conjugate acids* and *conjugate bases*, produced by the transfer of a proton from the acid to the base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In this approach, acids and bases are fundamentally different in behavior from salts, which are seen as electrolytes, subject to the theories of Debye, Onsager, and others.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] An acid and a base react not to produce a salt and a solvent, but to form a new acid and a new base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The concept of neutralization is thus absent.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base behavior is formally independent of any solvent, making it more all-encompassing than the Arrhenius model.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The calculation of pH under the Arrhenius model depended on alkalis (bases) dissolving in water (aqueous solution).
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model expanded what could be pH tested using insoluble and soluble solutions (gas, liquid, solid).
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The general formula for acid–base reactions according to the Brønsted–Lowry definition is: ${\ce {HA + B -> BH+ + A-}}$ where HA represents the acid, B represents the base, BH+ represents the conjugate acid of B, and A− represents the conjugate base of HA.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The removal of H+ from the HCl produces the chloride ion, Cl−, the conjugate base of the acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The addition of H+ to the H2O (acting as a base) forms the hydronium ion, H3O+, the conjugate acid of the base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Water is amphoteric – that is, it can act as both an acid and a base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Here, one molecule of water acts as an acid, donating an H+ and forming the conjugate base, OH−, and a second molecule of water acts as a base, accepting the H+ ion and forming the conjugate acid, H3O+.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In this example, a water molecule is split into a hydrogen cation, which is donated to a pyridine molecule, and a hydroxide ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In the Brønsted–Lowry model, the solvent does not necessarily have to be water, as is required by the Arrhenius Acid–Base model.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] An H+ ion is removed from acetic acid, forming its conjugate base, the acetate ion, CH3COO−.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The addition of an H+ ion to an ammonia molecule of the solvent creates its conjugate acid, the ammonium ion, NH+4.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Brønsted–Lowry model calls hydrogen-containing substances (like HCl) acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Thus, some substances, which many chemists considered to be acids, such as SO3 or BCl3, are excluded from this classification due to lack of hydrogen.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The hydrogen requirement of Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry was removed by the Lewis definition of acid–base reactions, devised by Gilbert N.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Lewis in 1923, in the same year as Brønsted–Lowry, but it was not elaborated by him until 1938.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Instead of defining acid–base reactions in terms of protons or other bonded substances, the Lewis definition defines a base (referred to as a *Lewis base*) to be a compound that can donate an *electron pair*, and an acid (a *Lewis acid*) to be a compound that can receive this electron pair.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] For example, boron trifluoride, BF3 is a typical Lewis acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] It can accept a pair of electrons as it has a vacancy in its octet.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The fluoride ion has a full octet and can donate a pair of electrons.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Thus ${\ce {BF3 + F- -> BF4-}}$ is a typical Lewis acid, Lewis base reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] All compounds of group 13 elements with a formula AX3 can behave as Lewis acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Similarly, compounds of group 15 elements with a formula DY3, such as amines, NR3, and phosphines, PR3, can behave as Lewis bases.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Adducts between them have the formula X3A←DY3 with a dative covalent bond, shown symbolically as ←, between the atoms A (acceptor) and D (donor).
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Compounds of group 16 with a formula DX2 may also act as Lewis bases; in this way, a compound like an ether, R2O, or a thioether, R2S, can act as a Lewis base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis definition is not limited to these examples.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] For instance, carbon monoxide acts as a Lewis base when it forms an adduct with boron trifluoride, of formula F3B←CO.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Adducts involving metal ions are referred to as co-ordination compounds; each ligand donates a pair of electrons to the metal ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The reaction ${\ce {[Ag(H2O)4]+ + 2 NH3 -> [Ag(NH3)2]+ + 4 H2O}}$ can be seen as an acid–base reaction in which a stronger base (ammonia) replaces a weaker one (water).
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The Lewis and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are consistent with each other since the reaction ${\ce {H+ + OH- <=> H2O}}$ is an acid–base reaction in both theories.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] One of the limitations of the Arrhenius definition is its reliance on water solutions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Edward Curtis Franklin studied the acid–base reactions in liquid ammonia in 1905 and pointed out the similarities to the water-based Arrhenius theory.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Germann, working with liquid phosgene, COCl 2, formulated the solvent-based theory in 1925, thereby generalizing the Arrhenius definition to cover aprotic solvents.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvonium ions and a decrease in the concentration of solvate ions is defined as an *acid*.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] A solute that causes an increase in the concentration of the solvate ions and a decrease in the concentration of the solvonium ions is defined as a *base*.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Thus, in liquid ammonia, KNH2 (supplying NH−2) is a strong base, and NH4NO3 (supplying NH+4) is a strong acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In liquid sulfur dioxide (SO2), thionyl compounds (supplying SO2+) behave as acids, and sulfites (supplying SO2−3) behave as bases.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] On the other hand, solvent system theory has been criticized as being too general to be useful.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Also, it has been thought that there is something intrinsically acidic about hydrogen compounds, a property not shared by non-hydrogenic solvonium salts.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This acid–base theory was a revival of the oxygen theory of acids and bases proposed by German chemist Hermann Lux in 1939, further improved by Håkon Flood c.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] 1947 and is still used in modern geochemistry and electrochemistry of molten salts.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This definition describes an acid as an oxide ion (O2−) acceptor and a base as an oxide ion donor.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This theory is also useful in the systematisation of the reactions of noble gas compounds, especially the xenon oxides, fluorides, and oxofluorides.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Mikhail Usanovich developed a general theory that does not restrict acidity to hydrogen-containing compounds, but his approach, published in 1938, was even more general than Lewis theory.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Usanovich's theory can be summarized as defining an acid as anything that accepts negative species or donates positive ones, and a base as the reverse.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This defined the concept of redox (oxidation-reduction) as a special case of acid–base reactions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In 1963, Ralph Pearson proposed a qualitative concept known as the Hard and Soft Acids and Bases principle. later made quantitative with help of Robert Parr in 1984.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] 'Hard' applies to species that are small, have high charge states, and are weakly polarizable.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] 'Soft' applies to species that are large, have low charge states and are strongly polarizable.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Acids and bases interact, and the most stable interactions are hard–hard and soft–soft.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] This theory has found use in organic and inorganic chemistry.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Drago is a quantitative model that describes and predicts the strength of Lewis acid base interactions, −Δ*H*.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The model assigned E and C parameters to many Lewis acids and bases.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Each acid is characterized by an *E*A and a *C*A.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Each base is likewise characterized by its own *E*B and *C*B.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The E and C parameters refer, respectively, to the electrostatic and covalent contributions to the strength of the bonds that the acid and base will form.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The W term represents a constant energy contribution for acid–base reaction such as the cleavage of a dimeric acid or base.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The equation predicts reversal of acids and base strengths.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The graphical presentations of the equation show that there is no single order of Lewis base strengths or Lewis acid strengths.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The reaction of a strong acid with a strong base is essentially a quantitative reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] In this reaction both the sodium and chloride ions are spectators as the neutralization reaction, ${\ce {H+ + OH- -> H2O}}$ does not involve them.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] With weak bases addition of acid is not quantitative because a solution of a weak base is a buffer solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] A solution of a weak acid is also a buffer solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] When a weak acid reacts with a weak base an equilibrium mixture is produced.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] The notation [X] signifies "concentration of X".
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] An acid–alkali reaction is a special case of an acid–base reaction, where the base used is also an alkali.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] When an acid reacts with an alkali salt (a metal hydroxide), the product is a metal salt and water.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Acid–alkali reactions are also neutralization reactions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Acids are in general pure substances that contain hydrogen cations (H+) or cause them to be produced in solutions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-base-reaction] Hydrochloric acid (HCl) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4) are common examples.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Acid–base property of the resulting solution from a neutralization reaction depends on the remaining salt products.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] A salt containing reactive cations undergo hydrolysis by which they react with water molecules, causing deprotonation of the conjugate acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Acid salts are often used in foods as part of leavening agents.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] In this context, the acid salts are referred to as *leavening acids*.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Common leavening acids include cream of tartar and monocalcium phosphate.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] An acid salt can be mixed with certain base salts (such as sodium bicarbonate (baking soda)) to create baking powders which release carbon dioxide.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Leavening agents can be slow-acting (e.g. sodium aluminum phosphate) which react when heated, or fast-acting (e.g., cream of tartar) which react immediately at low temperatures.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Double-acting baking powders contain both slow- and fast-acting leavening agents and react at low and high temperatures to provide even rising throughout the baking process.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Disodium phosphate, Na2HPO4, is used in foods and monosodium phosphate, NaH2PO4, is used in animal feed, toothpaste and evaporated milk.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] An acid with higher Ka value dominates the chemical reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] It serves as a better contributor of protons (H+).
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] The solution is alkaline if *Ka* < *Kb*.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Anions hydrolyze more than cations, causing an exceeding concentration of OH− ions.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] The solution is expected to be neutral only when *Ka* = *Kb*.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Other possible factors that could vary pH level of a solution are the relevant equilibrium constants and the additional amounts of any base or acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] For example, in ammonium chloride solution, NH+4 is the main influence for acidic solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] It has greater Ka value compared to that of water molecules; Ka of NH+4 is 5.6×10−10, and Kw of H2O is 1.0×10−14.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] This ensures its deprotonation when reacting with water, and is responsible for the pH below 7 at room temperature.
[src:baking-powder/acid-salt] Cl− will have no affinity for H+ nor tendency to hydrolyze, as its Kb value is very low (Kb of Cl− is 7.7×10−21).
[src:baking-powder/acid] An **acid** is a molecule or ion capable of either donating a proton (i.e. hydrogen cation, H+), known as a Brønsted–Lowry acid, or forming a covalent bond with an electron pair, known as a Lewis acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The first category of acids are the proton donors, or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the special case of aqueous solutions, proton donors form the hydronium ion H3O+ and are known as Arrhenius acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Brønsted and Lowry generalized the Arrhenius theory to include non-aqueous solvents.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A Brønsted–Lowry or Arrhenius acid usually contains a hydrogen atom bonded to a chemical structure that is still energetically favorable after loss of H+.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Aqueous Arrhenius acids have characteristic properties that provide a practical description of an acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acids form aqueous solutions with a sour taste, can turn blue litmus red, and react with bases and certain metals (like calcium) to form salts.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The word *acid* is derived from the Latin *acidus*, meaning 'sour'.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An aqueous solution of an acid has a pH less than 7 and is colloquially also referred to as "acid" (as in "dissolved in acid"), while the strict definition refers only to the solute.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A lower pH means a higher **acidity**, and thus a higher concentration of hydrogen cations in the solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Chemicals or substances having the property of an acid are said to be **acidic**.
[src:baking-powder/acid] As these examples show, acids (in the colloquial sense) can be solutions or pure substances, and can be derived from acids (in the strict sense) that are solids, liquids, or gases.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Strong acids and some concentrated weak acids are corrosive, but there are exceptions such as carboranes and boric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The second category of acids are Lewis acids, which form a covalent bond with an electron pair.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An example is boron trifluoride (BF3), whose boron atom has a vacant orbital that can form a covalent bond by sharing a lone pair of electrons on an atom in a base, for example the nitrogen atom in ammonia (NH3).
[src:baking-powder/acid] Lewis considered this as a generalization of the Brønsted definition, so that an acid is a chemical species that accepts electron pairs either directly *or* by releasing protons (H+) into the solution, which then accept electron pairs.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Hydrogen chloride, acetic acid, and most other Brønsted–Lowry acids cannot form a covalent bond with an electron pair, however, and are therefore not Lewis acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Conversely, many Lewis acids are not Arrhenius or Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In modern terminology, an *acid* is implicitly a Brønsted acid and not a Lewis acid, since chemists almost always refer to a Lewis acid explicitly as such.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Modern definitions are concerned with the fundamental chemical reactions common to all acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Most acids encountered in everyday life are aqueous solutions, or can be dissolved in water, so the Arrhenius and Brønsted–Lowry definitions are the most relevant.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The Brønsted–Lowry definition is the most widely used definition; unless otherwise specified, acid–base reactions are assumed to involve the transfer of a proton (H+) from an acid to a base.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Hydronium ions are acids according to all three definitions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Although alcohols and amines can be Brønsted–Lowry acids, they can also function as Lewis bases due to the lone pairs of electrons on their oxygen and nitrogen atoms.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In 1884, Svante Arrhenius attributed the properties of acidity to hydrogen cations (H+), later described as protons or hydrons.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An **Arrhenius acid** is a substance that, when added to water, increases the concentration of H+ ions in the water.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Chemists often write H+(*aq*) and refer to the hydrogen cation when describing acid–base reactions but the free hydrogen nucleus, a proton, does not exist alone in water, it exists as the **hydronium ion** (H3O+) or other forms (H5O2+, H9O4+).
[src:baking-powder/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid can also be described as a substance that increases the concentration of hydronium ions when added to water.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Examples include molecular substances such as hydrogen chloride and acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An Arrhenius base, on the other hand, is a substance that increases the concentration of hydroxide (OH−) ions when dissolved in water.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Due to this equilibrium, any increase in the concentration of hydronium is accompanied by a decrease in the concentration of hydroxide.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Thus, an Arrhenius acid could also be said to be one that decreases hydroxide concentration, while an Arrhenius base increases it.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In an acidic solution, the concentration of hydronium ions is greater than 10−7 moles per liter.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Since pH is defined as the negative logarithm of the concentration of hydronium ions, acidic solutions thus have a pH of less than 7.
[src:baking-powder/acid] While the Arrhenius concept is useful for describing many reactions, it is also quite limited in its scope.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In 1923, chemists Johannes Nicolaus Brønsted and Thomas Martin Lowry independently recognized that acid–base reactions involve the transfer of a proton.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A **Brønsted–Lowry acid** (or simply Brønsted acid) is a species that donates a proton to a Brønsted–Lowry base.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Brønsted–Lowry acid–base theory has several advantages over Arrhenius theory.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Both theories easily describe the first reaction: CH3COOH acts as an Arrhenius acid because it acts as a source of H3O+ when dissolved in water, and it acts as a Brønsted acid by donating a proton to water.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the second example CH3COOH undergoes the same transformation, in this case donating a proton to ammonia (NH3), but does not relate to the Arrhenius definition of an acid because the reaction does not produce hydronium.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Nevertheless, CH3COOH is both an Arrhenius and a Brønsted–Lowry acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Brønsted–Lowry theory can be used to describe reactions of molecular compounds in nonaqueous solution or the gas phase.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Hydrogen chloride (HCl) and ammonia combine under several different conditions to form ammonium chloride, NH4Cl.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In aqueous solution HCl behaves as hydrochloric acid and exists as hydronium and chloride ions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] As with the acetic acid reactions, both definitions work for the first example, where water is the solvent and hydronium ion is formed by the HCl solute.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The next two reactions do not involve the formation of ions but are still proton-transfer reactions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the second reaction hydrogen chloride and ammonia (dissolved in benzene) react to form solid ammonium chloride in a benzene solvent and in the third gaseous HCl and NH3 combine to form the solid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A third, only marginally related concept was proposed in 1923 by Gilbert N.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Lewis, which includes reactions with acid–base characteristics that do not involve a proton transfer.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A **Lewis acid** is a species that accepts a pair of electrons from another species; in other words, it is an electron pair acceptor.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Brønsted acid–base reactions are proton transfer reactions while Lewis acid–base reactions are electron pair transfers.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Many Lewis acids are not Brønsted–Lowry acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the first reaction a fluoride ion, F−, gives up an electron pair to boron trifluoride to form the product tetrafluoroborate.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Fluoride "loses" a pair of valence electrons because the electrons shared in the B—F bond are located in the region of space between the two atomic nuclei and are therefore more distant from the fluoride nucleus than they are in the lone fluoride ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid] BF3 is a Lewis acid because it accepts the electron pair from fluoride.
[src:baking-powder/acid] This reaction cannot be described in terms of Brønsted theory because there is no proton transfer.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The second reaction can be described using either theory.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A proton is transferred from an unspecified Brønsted acid to ammonia, a Brønsted base; alternatively, ammonia acts as a Lewis base and transfers a lone pair of electrons to form a bond with a hydrogen ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The species that gains the electron pair is the Lewis acid; for example, the oxygen atom in H3O+ gains a pair of electrons when one of the H—O bonds is broken and the electrons shared in the bond become localized on oxygen.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Depending on the context, a Lewis acid may also be described as an oxidizer or an electrophile.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Organic Brønsted acids, such as acetic, citric, or oxalic acid, are not Lewis acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] They dissociate in water to produce a Lewis acid, H+, but at the same time, they also yield an equal amount of a Lewis base (acetate, citrate, or oxalate, respectively, for the acids mentioned).
[src:baking-powder/acid] This article deals mostly with Brønsted acids rather than Lewis acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Reactions of acids are often generalized in the form HA ⇌ H+ + A−, where HA represents the acid and A− is the conjugate base.
[src:baking-powder/acid] This reaction is referred to as **protolysis**.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The protonated form (HA) of an acid is also sometimes referred to as the **free acid**.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acid–base conjugate pairs differ by one proton, and can be interconverted by the addition or removal of a proton (protonation and deprotonation, respectively).
[src:baking-powder/acid] The acid can be the charged species and the conjugate base can be neutral in which case the generalized reaction scheme could be written as HA+ ⇌ H+ + A.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In solution there exists an equilibrium between the acid and its conjugate base.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The equilibrium constant *K* is an expression of the equilibrium concentrations of the molecules or the ions in solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Brackets indicate concentration, such that [H2O] means *the concentration of H2O*.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The acid dissociation constant *K*a is generally used in the context of acid–base reactions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The numerical value of *K*a is equal to the product (multiplication) of the concentrations of the products divided by the concentration of the reactants, where the reactant is the acid (HA) and the products are the conjugate base and H+.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The stronger of two acids will have a higher *K*a than the weaker acid; the ratio of hydrogen cations to acid will be higher for the stronger acid as the stronger acid has a greater tendency to lose its proton.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Because the range of possible values for *K*a spans many orders of magnitude, a more manageable constant, p*K*a is more frequently used, where p*K*a = −log10 *K*a.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Stronger acids have a smaller p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Experimentally determined p*K*a at 25 °C in aqueous solution are often quoted in textbooks and reference material.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Arrhenius acids are named according to their anions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the classical naming system, the ionic suffix is dropped and replaced with a new suffix, according to the table following.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The prefix "hydro-" is used when the acid is made up of just hydrogen and one other element.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For example, HCl has chloride as its anion, so the hydro- prefix is used, and the -ide suffix makes the name take the form hydrochloric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the IUPAC naming system, "aqueous" is simply added to the name of the ionic compound.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Thus, for hydrogen chloride, as an acid solution, the IUPAC name is aqueous hydrogen chloride.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The strength of an acid refers to its ability or tendency to lose a proton.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A strong acid is one that completely dissociates in water; in other words, one mole of a strong acid HA dissolves in water yielding one mole of H+ and one mole of the conjugate base, A−, and none of the protonated acid HA.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In contrast, a weak acid only partially dissociates and at equilibrium both the acid and the conjugate base are in solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Examples of strong acids are hydrochloric acid (HCl), hydroiodic acid (HI), hydrobromic acid (HBr), perchloric acid (HClO4), nitric acid (HNO3) and sulfuric acid (H2SO4).
[src:baking-powder/acid] In water, each of these essentially ionizes 100%.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The stronger an acid is, the more easily it loses a proton, H+.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Two key factors that contribute to the ease of deprotonation are the polarity of the H—A bond and the size of atom A, which determines the strength of the H—A bond.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acid strengths are also often discussed in terms of the stability of the conjugate base.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Stronger acids have a larger acid dissociation constant, *K*a and a lower p*K*a than weaker acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Sulfonic acids, which are organic oxyacids, are a class of strong acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A common example is toluenesulfonic acid (tosylic acid).
[src:baking-powder/acid] Unlike sulfuric acid itself, sulfonic acids can be solids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In fact, polystyrene functionalized into polystyrene sulfonate is a solid strongly acidic plastic that is filterable.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Superacids are acids stronger than 100% sulfuric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Examples of superacids are fluoroantimonic acid, magic acid and perchloric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The strongest known acid is helium hydride ion, with a proton affinity of 177.8kJ/mol.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Superacids can permanently protonate water to give ionic, crystalline hydronium "salts".
[src:baking-powder/acid] They can also quantitatively stabilize carbocations.
[src:baking-powder/acid] While *K*a measures the strength of an acid compound, the strength of an aqueous acid solution is measured by pH, which is an indication of the concentration of hydronium in the solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The pH of a simple solution of an acid compound in water is determined by the dilution of the compound and the compound's *K*a.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Lewis acids have been classified in the ECW model and it has been shown that there is no one order of acid strengths.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The relative acceptor strength of Lewis acids toward a series of bases, versus other Lewis acids, can be illustrated by C-B plots.
[src:baking-powder/acid] It has been shown that to define the order of Lewis acid strength at least two properties must be considered.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For Pearson's qualitative HSAB theory the two properties are hardness and strength while for Drago's quantitative ECW model the two properties are electrostatic and covalent.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Common examples of monoprotic acids in mineral acids include hydrochloric acid (HCl) and nitric acid (HNO3).
[src:baking-powder/acid] On the other hand, for organic acids the term mainly indicates the presence of one carboxylic acid group and sometimes these acids are known as monocarboxylic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Examples in organic acids include formic acid (HCOOH), acetic acid (CH3COOH) and benzoic acid (C6H5COOH).
[src:baking-powder/acid] Polyprotic acids, also known as polybasic acids, are able to donate more than one proton per acid molecule, in contrast to monoprotic acids that only donate one proton per molecule.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Specific types of polyprotic acids have more specific names, such as diprotic (or dibasic) acid (two potential protons to donate), and triprotic (or tribasic) acid (three potential protons to donate).
[src:baking-powder/acid] Some macromolecules such as proteins and nucleic acids can have a very large number of acidic protons.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A diprotic acid (here symbolized by H2A) can undergo one or two dissociations depending on the pH.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Each dissociation has its own dissociation constant, Ka1 and Ka2.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The first dissociation constant is typically greater than the second (i.e., *K*a1 > *K*a2).
[src:baking-powder/acid] For example, sulfuric acid (H2SO4) can donate one proton to form the bisulfate anion (HSO− 4), for which *K*a1 is very large; then it can donate a second proton to form the sulfate anion (SO2− 4), wherein the *K*a2 is intermediate strength.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The large *K*a1 for the first dissociation makes sulfuric a strong acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In a similar manner, the weak unstable carbonic acid (H2CO3) can lose one proton to form bicarbonate anion (HCO− 3) and lose a second to form carbonate anion (CO2− 3).
[src:baking-powder/acid] Both *K*a values are small, but *K*a1 > *K*a2 .
[src:baking-powder/acid] A triprotic acid (H3A) can undergo one, two, or three dissociations and has three dissociation constants, where *K*a1 > *K*a2 > *K*a3.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An inorganic example of a triprotic acid is orthophosphoric acid (H3PO4), usually just called phosphoric acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] All three protons can be successively lost to yield H2PO− 4, then HPO2− 4, and finally PO3− 4, the orthophosphate ion, usually just called phosphate.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Even though the positions of the three protons on the original phosphoric acid molecule are equivalent, the successive *K*a values differ since it is energetically less favorable to lose a proton if the conjugate base is more negatively charged.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An organic example of a triprotic acid is citric acid, which can successively lose three protons to finally form the citrate ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Although the subsequent loss of each hydrogen ion is less favorable, all of the conjugate bases are present in solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The fractional concentration, *α* (alpha), for each species can be calculated.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For example, a generic diprotic acid will generate 3 species in solution: H2A, HA−, and A2−.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A plot of these fractional concentrations against pH, for given *K*1 and *K*2, is known as a Bjerrum plot.
[src:baking-powder/acid] where *K*0 = 1 and the other K-terms are the dissociation constants for the acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Neutralization is the basis of titration, where a pH indicator shows equivalence point when the equivalent number of moles of a base have been added to an acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] It is often wrongly assumed that neutralization should result in a solution with pH 7.0, which is only the case with similar acid and base strengths during a reaction.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Neutralization with a base weaker than the acid results in a weakly acidic salt.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An example is the weakly acidic ammonium chloride, which is produced from the strong acid hydrogen chloride and the weak base ammonia.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Conversely, neutralizing a weak acid with a strong base gives a weakly basic salt (e.g., sodium fluoride from hydrogen fluoride and sodium hydroxide).
[src:baking-powder/acid] In order for a protonated acid to lose a proton, the pH of the system must rise above the p*K*a of the acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The decreased concentration of H+ in that basic solution shifts the equilibrium towards the conjugate base form (the deprotonated form of the acid).
[src:baking-powder/acid] In lower-pH (more acidic) solutions, there is a high enough H+ concentration in the solution to cause the acid to remain in its protonated form.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Solutions of weak acids and salts of their conjugate bases form buffer solutions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] To determine the concentration of an acid in an aqueous solution, an acid–base titration is commonly performed.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A strong base solution with a known concentration, usually NaOH or KOH, is added to neutralize the acid solution according to the color change of the indicator with the amount of base added.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The titration curve of an acid titrated by a base has two axes, with the base volume on the x-axis and the solution's pH value on the y-axis.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The pH of the solution always goes up as the base is added to the solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For each diprotic acid titration curve, from left to right, there are two midpoints, two equivalence points, and two buffer regions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Due to the successive dissociation processes, there are two equivalence points in the titration curve of a diprotic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The first equivalence point occurs when all first protons from the first ionization are titrated.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In other words, the amount of OH− added equals the original amount of H2A at the first equivalence point.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The second equivalence point occurs when all protons are titrated.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Therefore, the amount of OH− added equals twice the amount of H2A at this time.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For a weak diprotic acid titrated by a strong base, the second equivalence point must occur at pH above 7 due to the hydrolysis of the resulted salts in the solution.
[src:baking-powder/acid] At either equivalence point, adding a drop of base will cause the steepest rise of the pH value in the system.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A titration curve for a diprotic acid contains two midpoints where pH=pKa.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Since there are two different Ka values, the first midpoint occurs at pH=pKa1 and the second one occurs at pH=pKa2.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Each segment of the curve that contains a midpoint at its center is called the buffer region.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Because the buffer regions consist of the acid and its conjugate base, it can resist pH changes when base is added until the next equivalent points.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acids are fundamental reagents in treating almost all processes in modern industry.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Sulfuric acid, a diprotic acid, is the most widely used acid in industry, and is also the most-produced industrial chemical in the world.
[src:baking-powder/acid] It is mainly used in producing fertilizer, detergent, batteries and dyes, as well as used in processing many products such like removing impurities.
[src:baking-powder/acid] According to the statistics data in 2011, the annual production of sulfuric acid was around 200 million tonnes in the world.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For example, phosphate minerals react with sulfuric acid to produce phosphoric acid for the production of phosphate fertilizers, and zinc is produced by dissolving zinc oxide into sulfuric acid, purifying the solution and electrowinning.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In the chemical industry, acids react in neutralization reactions to produce salts.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For example, nitric acid reacts with ammonia to produce ammonium nitrate, a fertilizer.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Additionally, carboxylic acids can be esterified with alcohols, to produce esters.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acids are often used to remove rust and other corrosion from metals in a process known as pickling.
[src:baking-powder/acid] They may be used as an electrolyte in a wet cell battery, such as sulfuric acid in a car battery.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Tartaric acid is an important component of some commonly used foods like unripe mangoes and tamarind.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Natural fruits and vegetables also contain acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Citric acid is present in oranges, lemon and other citrus fruits.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Oxalic acid is present in tomatoes, spinach, and especially in carambola and rhubarb; rhubarb leaves and unripe carambolas are toxic because of high concentrations of oxalic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) is an essential vitamin for the human body and is present in such foods as amla (Indian gooseberry), lemon, citrus fruits, and guava.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Many acids can be found in various kinds of food as additives, as they alter their taste and serve as preservatives.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Phosphoric acid, for example, is a component of cola drinks.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acetic acid is used in day-to-day life as vinegar.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Citric acid is used as a preservative in sauces and pickles.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Carbonic acid is one of the most common acid additives that are widely added in soft drinks.
[src:baking-powder/acid] During the manufacturing process, CO2 is usually pressurized to dissolve in these drinks to generate carbonic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Carbonic acid is very unstable and tends to decompose into water and CO2 at room temperature and pressure.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Therefore, when bottles or cans of these kinds of soft drinks are opened, the soft drinks fizz and effervesce as CO2 bubbles come out.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acetylsalicylic acid (Aspirin) is used as a pain killer and for bringing down fevers.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acids play important roles in the human body.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The hydrochloric acid present in the stomach aids digestion by breaking down large and complex food molecules.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Amino acids are required for synthesis of proteins required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Fatty acids are also required for growth and repair of body tissues.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Nucleic acids are important for the manufacturing of DNA and RNA and transmitting of traits to offspring through genes.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Carbonic acid is important for maintenance of pH equilibrium in the body.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Human bodies contain a variety of organic and inorganic compounds, among those dicarboxylic acids play an essential role in many biological behaviors.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Many of those acids are amino acids, which mainly serve as materials for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Other weak acids serve as buffers with their conjugate bases to keep the body's pH from undergoing large scale changes that would be harmful to cells.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The rest of the dicarboxylic acids also participate in the synthesis of various biologically important compounds in human bodies.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acids are used as catalysts in industrial and organic chemistry; for example, sulfuric acid is used in very large quantities in the alkylation process to produce gasoline.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Some acids, such as sulfuric, phosphoric, and hydrochloric acids, also effect dehydration and condensation reactions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In biochemistry, many enzymes employ acid catalysis.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Many biologically important molecules are acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Nucleic acids, which contain acidic phosphate groups, include DNA and RNA.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Nucleic acids contain the genetic code that determines many of an organism's characteristics, and is passed from parents to offspring.
[src:baking-powder/acid] DNA contains the chemical blueprint for the synthesis of proteins, which are made up of amino acid subunits.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Cell membranes contain fatty acid esters such as phospholipids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] An α-amino acid has a central carbon (the α or *alpha* carbon) that is covalently bonded to a carboxyl group (thus they are carboxylic acids), an amino group, a hydrogen atom and a variable group.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The variable group, also called the R group or side chain, determines the identity and many of the properties of a specific amino acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In glycine, the simplest amino acid, the R group is a hydrogen atom, but in all other amino acids it is contains one or more carbon atoms bonded to hydrogens, and may contain other elements such as sulfur, oxygen or nitrogen.
[src:baking-powder/acid] With the exception of glycine, naturally occurring amino acids are chiral and almost invariably occur in the L-configuration.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Peptidoglycan, found in some bacterial cell walls contains some D-amino acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] At physiological pH, typically around 7, free amino acids exist in a charged form, where the acidic carboxyl group (-COOH) loses a proton (-COO−) and the basic amine group (-NH2) gains a proton (-NH+ 3).
[src:baking-powder/acid] The entire molecule has a net neutral charge and is a zwitterion, with the exception of amino acids with basic or acidic side chains.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Aspartic acid, for example, possesses one protonated amine and two deprotonated carboxyl groups, for a net charge of −1 at physiological pH.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Fatty acids and fatty acid derivatives are another group of carboxylic acids that play a significant role in biology.
[src:baking-powder/acid] These contain long hydrocarbon chains and a carboxylic acid group on one end.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The cell membrane of nearly all organisms is primarily made up of a phospholipid bilayer, a micelle of hydrophobic fatty acid esters with polar, hydrophilic phosphate "head" groups.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Membranes contain additional components, some of which can participate in acid–base reactions.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In humans and many other animals, hydrochloric acid is a part of the gastric acid secreted within the stomach to help hydrolyze proteins and polysaccharides, as well as converting the inactive pro-enzyme, pepsinogen into the enzyme, pepsin.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Some organisms produce acids for defense; for example, ants produce formic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acid–base equilibrium plays a critical role in regulating mammalian breathing.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Oxygen gas (O2) drives cellular respiration, the process by which animals release the chemical potential energy stored in food, producing carbon dioxide (CO2) as a byproduct.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Oxygen and carbon dioxide are exchanged in the lungs, and the body responds to changing energy demands by adjusting the rate of ventilation.
[src:baking-powder/acid] For example, during periods of exertion the body rapidly breaks down stored carbohydrates and fat, releasing CO2 into the blood stream.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In aqueous solutions such as blood CO2 exists in equilibrium with carbonic acid and bicarbonate ion.
[src:baking-powder/acid] It is the decrease in pH that signals the brain to breathe faster and deeper, expelling the excess CO2 and resupplying the cells with O2.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Cell membranes are generally impermeable to charged or large, polar molecules because of the lipophilic fatty acyl chains comprising their interior.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Many biologically important molecules, including a number of pharmaceutical agents, are organic weak acids that can cross the membrane in their protonated, uncharged form but not in their charged form (i.e., as the conjugate base).
[src:baking-powder/acid] For this reason the activity of many drugs can be enhanced or inhibited by the use of antacids or acidic foods.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The charged form, however, is often more soluble in blood and cytosol, both aqueous environments.
[src:baking-powder/acid] When the extracellular environment is more acidic than the neutral pH within the cell, certain acids will exist in their neutral form and will be membrane soluble, allowing them to cross the phospholipid bilayer.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Acids that lose a proton at the intracellular pH will exist in their soluble, charged form and are thus able to diffuse through the cytosol to their target.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Ibuprofen, aspirin and penicillin are examples of drugs that are weak acids.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A sulfonic acid has the general formula RS(=O)2–OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:baking-powder/acid] A carboxylic acid has the general formula R-C(O)OH, where R is an organic radical.
[src:baking-powder/acid] The carboxyl group -C(O)OH contains a carbonyl group, C=O, and a hydroxyl group, O-H.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Halogenation at alpha position increases acid strength, so that the following acids are all stronger than acetic acid.
[src:baking-powder/acid] Normal carboxylic acids are the direct union of a carbonyl group and a hydroxyl group.
[src:baking-powder/acid] In vinylogous carboxylic acids, a carbon-carbon double bond separates the carbonyl and hydroxyl groups.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Egg white makes up around two-thirds of a chicken egg by weight.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Water constitutes about 90% of this, with protein, trace minerals, fatty material, vitamins, and glucose contributing the remainder.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] A raw U.S. large egg contains around 33 grams of egg white with 3.6 grams of protein, 0.24 grams of carbohydrate and 55 milligrams of sodium.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] It contains no cholesterol and the energy content is about 17 calories.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Egg white is an alkaline solution and contains around 149 proteins.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] The table below lists the major proteins in egg whites by percentage and their natural functions.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Ovalbumin is the most abundant protein in albumen.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Classed as phosphoglycoprotein, during storage, it converts into s-ovalbumin (5% at the time of laying) and can reach up to 80% after six months of cold storage.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Ovalbumin in solution is heat-resistant.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Denaturation temperature is around 84 °C, but it can be easily denatured by physical stress.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Conalbumin/ovotransferrin is a glycoprotein which has the capacity to bind the bi- and trivalent metal cations into a complex and is more heat sensitive than ovalbumin.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] At its isoelectric pH (6.5), it can bind two cations and assume a red or yellow color.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] These metal complexes are more heat stable than the native state.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Ovomucoid is the major allergen from egg white and is a heat-resistant glycoprotein found to be a trypsin inhibitor.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Lysozyme is a holoprotein which can lyse the wall of certain Gram-positive bacteria and is found at high levels in the chalaziferous layer and the chalazae which anchor the yolk towards the middle of the egg.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Ovomucin is a glycoprotein which may contribute to the gel-like structure of thick albumen.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] The amount of ovomucin in the thick albumen is four times as great as in the thin albumen.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] The physical stress of beating egg whites can create a foam.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Two types of physical stress are caused by beating them with a whisk: denaturation and coagulation.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Denaturation occurs as the whisk drags the liquid through itself, creating a force that unfolds the protein molecules.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Coagulation comes from the mixing of air into the whites, which causes the proteins to come out of their natural state.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] When beating egg whites, they are classified in three stages according to the peaks they form when the beater is lifted: soft, firm, and stiff peaks.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Overbeaten eggs take on a dry appearance, and eventually collapse.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Egg whites do not beat up correctly if they are exposed to any form of fat, such as cooking oils or the fats contained in egg yolk.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Copper bowls have been used in France since the 18th century to stabilize egg foams.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] The copper in the bowl assists in creating a tighter bond in reactive sulfur items such as egg whites.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] The bond created is so tight that the sulfurs are prevented from reacting with any other material.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] A silver-plated bowl has the same result as the copper bowl, as will a pinch of powdered copper supplement from a health store used in a glass bowl.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Drawbacks of the copper bowl include the expense of the bowl itself, and that the bowls are difficult to keep clean.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Copper contamination from the bowl is minimal, as a cup of foam contains a tenth of a human's normal daily intake level.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Although egg whites are prized as a source of low-fat, high-protein nutrition, a small number of people cannot eat them.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Egg allergy is more common among infants than adults, and most children will outgrow it by the age of five.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Allergic reactions against egg white are more common than reactions against egg yolks.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] In addition to true allergic reactions, some people experience a food intolerance to egg whites.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Eggs are susceptible to *Salmonella* contamination.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Thorough cooking eliminates the direct threat (i.e. cooked egg whites that are solid and not runny), but the threat of cross-contamination remains if people handle contaminated eggs and then touch other foods or items in the kitchen, thus spreading the bacteria.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] In August 2010, the FDA ordered the recall of 380 million eggs because of possible *Salmonella* contamination.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Cooked eggs are a good source of biotin.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] However, daily consumption of raw egg whites for several months may result in biotin deficiency, due to their avidin content, as the avidin tightly binds biotin and prevents its absorption.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Egg white is a fining agent that can be used in the clarification and stabilization of wine.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Egg white can also be added to shaken cocktails to create a delicate froth.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] Some protein powders also use egg whites as a primary source of protein.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] The albumen from egg white was used as a binding agent in early photography during an 1855–90 period; such prints were called albumen prints.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] In bookbinding, egg white (called glaire in this context) is used to adhere gold leaf in gold tooling.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] In manuscripts, egg white (or yolk) can be used as a binder for pigments.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] In the 1750s, egg whites were believed to prevent swelling, and were used for that purpose.
[src:baking-powder/albumen] To help soothe areas of skin that were afflicted, egg white mixed with Armenian bole could help restore the fibers.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Alfred Bird served a pharmacist apprenticeship to Philip Harris Ltd. in Birmingham.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Bird became a qualified chemist and druggist.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] In 1837, Bird opened a shop in Bull Street, Birmingham, *Alfred Bird, experimental chemist*.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] In 1837, Bird's first major invention was egg-free custard.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Alfred Bird used cornflour instead of egg to create an imitation of egg custard.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] It was originally intended only for his wife Elizabeth who had both egg and yeast allergies.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] The Birds used genuine custard when entertaining guests, but on one occasion the egg-free custard was (either by accident or design) fed to dinner guests.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] It was well received, and Alfred Bird realised that his invention had a wider use.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Soon afterwards Alfred Bird founded 'Alfred Bird and Sons Ltd', which would go on to become the famous Bird's Custard company and brand.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] In 1842, Bird registered as a pharmacist in Birmingham.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] In 1843, Bird invented *Bird's Fermenting Powder*, a baking powder, to make yeast-free bread for his wife.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] This formula for baking powder is similar to modern baking powders.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Alfred Bird died on 15 December 1878 in Kings Norton, Birmingham and is buried at Key Hill Cemetery in Birmingham.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Famously his obituary in the journal of the Chemical Society (of which he was a fellow) discussed at length his skills and research but did not mention his other activity – the by then famous Bird's Custard and Bird's Jelly.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] His son, Alfred Frederick Bird, continued the work of his father.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] Bird junior went on to invent egg substitute powder in 1890, blancmange powder and jelly powder.
[src:baking-powder/alfred-bird] The Custard Factory in Digbeth, Birmingham, is now a centre providing space to artists.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1843, the first *single-acting* baking powder (meaning that it releases all of its carbon dioxide as soon as it is dampened) was developed by pharmacist Alfred Bird in England.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1856, Eben Norton Horsford, the Rumford Professor at Harvard University, received an American patent, for monocalcium phosphate, for baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In the 1860s, Eben Norton Horsford developed the first *double-acting* baking powder, which releases some carbon dioxide when dampened and later releases more of the gas when heated by baking.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking powder is used instead of yeast for end-products where fermentation flavors would be undesirable, or where the batter lacks the elastic structure to hold gas bubbles for more than a few minutes, and to speed the production of baked goods.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Because carbon dioxide is released at a faster rate through the acid–base reaction than through fermentation, breads made by chemical leavening are called quick breads.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The introduction of baking powder was revolutionary in minimizing the time and labor required to make breadstuffs.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] It led to the creation of new types of cakes, cookies, biscuits, and other baked goods.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking powder is made up of a base, an acid, and a desiccant to prevent the acid and base from reacting before their intended use.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Most commercially available baking powders are made up of sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3, also known as baking soda or bicarbonate of soda) and one or more acid salts.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] When combined with water, the sodium bicarbonate and acid salts react to produce gaseous carbon dioxide.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The use of two acidic components is the basis of the term "double acting".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The acid in a baking powder can be either fast-acting or slow-acting.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] A fast-acting acid reacts in a wet mixture with baking soda at room temperature, and a slow-acting acid does not react until heated.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] When the chemical reactions in baking powders involve both fast- and slow-acting acids, they are known as "double-acting"; those that contain only one acid are "single-acting".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] By providing a second rise in the oven, double-acting baking powders increase the reliability of baked goods by rendering the time elapsed between mixing and baking less critical.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] This is the type of baking powder most widely available to consumers today.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Double-acting baking powders work in two phases; once when cold, and once when hot.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Thus, a double-acting baking powder, with baking soda, uses fast-acting acid that reacts in a cool (room temperature), wet mixture.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Later, after heating, the slower-acting acid reacts, with baking soda, in the wet mixture, at the now-high-temperature.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Slower-acting acids only react at higher than room temperatures.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] However, Rumford Baking Powder is a double-acting product that contains only one leavening acid, monocalcium phosphate.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] With this acid, about two-thirds of the available gas is released within about two minutes of mixing at room temperature.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] It then becomes dormant because an intermediate species, dicalcium phosphate, is generated during the initial mixing.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] A further release of gas requires the batter to be heated above 140 °F (60 °C).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Common low-temperature acid salts include cream of tartar and monocalcium phosphate (also called calcium acid phosphate).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] High-temperature acid salts include sodium aluminium sulfate, sodium aluminium phosphate, and sodium acid pyrophosphate.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking powders also include components to improve their stability and consistency.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Cornstarch, flour, or potato starch are often used as desiccants An inert starch serves several functions in baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Primarily it is used to absorb moisture, and so prolong shelf life of the compound by keeping the powder's alkaline and acidic components dry so as not to react with each other prematurely.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] A dry powder also flows and mixes more easily.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Finally, the added bulk allows for more accurate measurements.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking powder is made of two main components: an acid and a bicarbonate base.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] When they are hydrated, an acid–base reaction occurs, releasing carbon dioxide.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The neutralizing value (NV) is defined as the amount of baking soda required to neutralize 100 parts of a leavening acid (by weight).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The rate of reaction (ROR) is represented by the percentage of carbon dioxide released by the acid-base reaction.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Other subcategories exist to classify the reaction rated during mixing and holding called “Dough Reaction Rate (DRR)” and during baking at a given temperature denominated “Batter Reaction Rate (BRR)”.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] When Amelia Simmons published *American Cookery* (1792), the first American cookbook, three known types of leavening were used in its recipes: baker's yeast, emptins (from the leavings of brewer's yeast), and pearlash.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] At that time, the mechanisms underlying the action of yeasts and other leavenings were not understood, and reliable commercial products were not available.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Bakers obtained yeasts from brewers or distillers or made their own by exposing mixtures of flour and water to the open air.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] If lucky, they could capture useful wild yeast and keep some alive, regularly feeding it for ongoing use and trying to avoid contamination.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Women who made their own ale could use the brewing dregs or "emptins" in their baking.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The effectiveness of such leavenings varied widely.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Resulting baked goods often had a sour or bitter taste.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Breads were made of grain, water, yeast, and sometimes salt.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Cooks also made yeast, sponge and pound cakes.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Yeast cakes were similar to breads but included fancier ingredients, like sugar, spices, fruits or nuts.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Sponge cakes used beaten egg whites for leavening.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Pound cakes combined butter, sugar, and flour and eggs, and were particularly dense.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Making cakes was even more laborious than making bread: to prepare a cake, a manservant might have to beat the ingredients together as long as an hour.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The third type of leavening, pearlash, was the precursor to modern baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] According to Joop Witteveen (1985), pearlash was used in Europe by professional bakers in the mid-seventeenth century.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The *Oxford English Dictionary* credits the first written use of the term "pearl ash" to 1703 and the writing of Abel Boyer.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] By the mid-1700s, practical treatises on the calcination of pearlash were available in both England and the United States.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Pearlash was the subject of the first patent in the United States, issued in April 1790.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Its preparation was time-consuming, but could be accomplished with a cast-iron kettle: it involved soaking fireplace ashes in water to make lye, and then boiling the lye to remove water and obtain "salts".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The active ingredient in pearlash was potassium carbonate (K2CO3).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Combining it with an acidic ingredient like sour milk or lemon juice resulted in a chemical reaction that produced carbon dioxide.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Once prepared, the white powder was much more stable than yeast.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Small amounts could be used on a daily basis, rather than baking a week or two weeks' worth of bread at one time.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] *American Cookery* was the first cookbook to call for its use, but by no means the last.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] With pearlash, cooks were able to create new recipes for new types of cakes, cookies, and biscuits that were quicker and easier to make than yeast-based recipes.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Between the publication of *American Cookery* in 1796, and the mid-1800s, cooks experimented with a variety of acids, alkalis, and mineral salts as possible chemical leaveners.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Many were already available in households as medicinal, cleaning or solvent products.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Smelling salts, hartshorn, and sal volatile were all ammonia inhalants, containing forms of ammonium carbonate.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The term "saleratus" was applied confusingly to both potassium bicarbonate and to sodium bicarbonate (NaHCO3, what we now call baking soda).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking soda and cream of tartar were relatively new ingredients for cooks: Soda may have been introduced to American cooking by female Irish immigrants who found work as kitchen help.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Cream of tartar, also known as tartaric acid or potassium bitartrate, was a by-product of wine-making and had to be imported from France and Italy.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1846, the first edition of Catherine Beecher's cookbook *Domestic Recipe Book* (1846) included a recipe for an early prototype of baking powder biscuits that used both baking soda and cream of tartar.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Several recipes in the cookbook compiled by Elizabeth Hall *Practical American Cookery* (1856) used baking soda and cream of tartar to form new types of dough.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] There were recipes for a "crust" similar to modern dumplings or cobbler, several for cakes, and one for "soda doughnuts".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] When the third edition of *Miss Beecher's Domestic Receipt Book* appeared in 1858, it included 8 types of leaveners, only two of which could be made at home.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking soda and cream of tartar were sold by chemists rather than in grocery stores.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Pharmacists purchased the materials in bulk and then dispensed them individually in small amounts in paper packaging.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] At least one contributor to *Practical American Cookery* provided instructions on how to handle baking soda and cream of tartar.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Even with instructions, early leaveners could be difficult to obtain, awkward to store, unstandardized, and unpredictable to use.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The chemical leavening effects were accomplished by the activating of a base such as baking soda in the presence of liquid(s) and an acid such as sour milk, vinegar, lemon juice, or cream of tartar.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Because these acidulants react with baking soda quickly, retention of gas bubbles was dependent on batter viscosity.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] It was critical for the batter to be baked quickly, before the gas escaped.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The next step, the development of baking powder, created a system where the gas-producing reactions could be delayed until needed.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The creation of shelf-stable chemical combinations of sodium bicarbonate and cream of tartar is seen as marking the true introduction of baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Although cooks had used both sodium bicarbonate and cream of tartar in recipes, they had to purchase the ingredients individually and store them separately to prevent them from spoiling or reacting prematurely.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] As chemists developed more uniform constituents, they also began to experiment with ways of combining them.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In the mid-late 1800s, chemists introduced the first modern baking powders.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1843, the first to create a form of baking powder was English chemist and food manufacturer Alfred Bird.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Bird was motivated to develop a yeast-free leavener because his wife Elizabeth was allergic to eggs and yeast.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] His formulation included bicarbonate of soda and tartaric acid, mixed with starch to absorb moisture and prevent the other ingredients from reacting.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] A single-action form of baking powder, *Bird's Fermenting Powder*, a *baking powder*, later, *Alfred Bird's Baking Powder*, reacted as soon as it became damp.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Bird focused on selling his baking powder to the British Army during the Crimean War, and to explorers like Captain Sir Francis Leopold McClintock, rather than the domestic market.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Nonetheless, Bird's creation of baking powder enabled cooks to take recipes for cakes such as the patriotically named Victoria sponge and make them rise higher.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] He did not patent his discovery, and others such as Henry Jones of Bristol soon produced and patented similar products.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1845, Jones patented "A new preparation of flour" (self-raising flour) that included sodium bicarbonate and tartaric acid to obtain a leavening effect.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In America, Eben Norton Horsford, a student of Justus von Liebig, set out to create a flour fortifier and leavening agent.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1856, he was awarded a patent for "pulverulent phosphoric acid", a process for extracting monocalcium pyrophosphate extracted from bones.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Horsford's use of monocalcium pyrophosphate eliminated the need for cream of tartar, which was expensively imported from France and required separate storage.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Combined with baking soda, monocalcium pyrophosphate provided a double-acting form of leavening.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Its initial reaction, when exposed to water, released carbon dioxide and produced dicalcium phosphate, which then reacted under heat to release second-stage carbon dioxide.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1859, Horsford, the Rumford Professor and Lecturer on the Application of Science to the Useful Arts at Harvard, and George Wilson formed the Rumford Chemical Works, named in honor of Count Rumford (Benjamin Thompson).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1861, Horsford published *The theory and art of breadmaking: A new process without the use of ferment*, describing his innovations.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1864, he obtained a patent for a self-rising flour or "Bread preparation" in which calcium acid phosphate and sodium bicarbonate acted as a leavener.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Horsford's research was interrupted by the American Civil War, but in 1869 Horsford finally created an already-mixed leavening agent by using cornstarch as a desiccant.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Rumford Chemical Works then began the manufacture of what can be considered a true baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Throughout his career, Horsford continued to experiment extensively with possible techniques and preparations for baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Horsford's leavening products were marketed originally as "Horsford's Yeast Powder" and later as "Rumford Baking Powder".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] They were packaged in glass bottles and later in metal cans.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 2006 the Rumford Chemical Works in East Providence, Rhode Island were designated a National Historic Chemical Landmark in recognition of baking powder's impact in making baking easier, quicker, and more reliable.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In the 1860s, Horsford shared his formula for baking powder with his former teacher, Justus von Liebig, who in turn shared it with Ludwig Clamor Marquart and Carl Zimmer in Germany.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking powders based on Horsford's formula were sold in England as "Horsford-Liebig Baking Powder".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] They were also sold by several companies in Germany, beginning with Marquart and with Zimmer.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] However, baking powder was not successful in Germany at that time.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Much of German baking occurred in guild-based bakeries, rather than in private homes, and the guilds were not interested in replacing centuries-old craft skills with a new technology.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In the 1890s, the German pharmacist August Oetker began to market a baking powder directly to housewives.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Oetker's Baking Powder" and as "Backin".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Oetker started the mass production of phosphate-based baking powder in 1898 and patented his technique in 1903.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Jones in 1993 has shown that Oetker's original recipe was a descendant of Horsford's phosphate-based recipe, obtained from Louis Marquand, a son of Ludwig Clamor Marquart.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Oetker Baking Powder continues to be sold, currently listing its ingredients as sodium acid pyrophosphate, sodium bicarbonate and corn starch.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Hoagland and his brother Cornelius developed a baking powder product with the help of Thomas M.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] They sold a single-action baking powder containing cream of tartar, bicarbonate of soda and starch.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Their formula became known as Royal Baking Powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Initially in partnership as Biddle & Hoagland, the Hoaglands moved from Fort Wayne, Indiana, to Chicago, leaving Biddle behind, and then to New York.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] They incorporated there as the Royal Baking Powder Company in 1868.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Various battles for control ensued between the Hoagland brothers and their one-time employee William Ziegler.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Finally, on March 2, 1899, Ziegler established the New Jersey–based Royal Baking Powder Corporation which combined the three major cream of tartar baking powder companies then in existence in the United States: Dr.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Price (Ziegler), Royal (Joseph Hoagland) and Cleveland (Cornelius Nevius Hoagland).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Cream of tartar was an expensive ingredient in the United States, since it had to be imported from France.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In the 1880s, several companies developed double-action baking powders containing cheaper alternative acids known as alums, a class of compounds involving double sulfates of aluminium.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The use of various types of alum in medicines and dyes is mentioned in Pliny the Elder's *Natural History*.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] However, the actual composition of alum was not determined until 1798, when Louis Vauquelin demonstrated that common alum is a double salt, composed of sulfuric acid, alumina, and potash. and Jean-Antoine Chaptal published the analysis of four different kinds of alum.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1888, William Monroe Wright (a former salesman for Dr.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Price) and George Campbell Rew in Chicago introduced a new form of baking powder, which they called Calumet.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Calumet Baking Powder contained baking soda, a cornstarch desiccant, sodium aluminium sulfate (NaAl(SO 4) 2·12H 2O) as a leavening agent, and albumen.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 1899, after years of experimentation with various possible formulae beginning in the 1870s, Herman Hulman of Terre Haute also introduced a baking powder made with sodium aluminium sulfate.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] He called his baking powder Clabber, referencing a German baking tradition in which soured milk was used for leavening.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Sodium aluminium sulfate baking powders were double-acting, and much less expensive to produce than cream of tartar-based baking powders.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Cooks also needed less alum-based baking powder to produce a comparable effect.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] As a result, alum-based baking powders were severe competition for Royal Baking Powder's cream of tartar-based products.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] William Ziegler of the Royal Baking Powder Company used a variety of tactics, ranging from false advertising and industrial espionage to bribery, to try to convince consumers and legislators that aluminium-based baking powders were harmful.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] He suggested (without actual evidence) that alum was unnatural and poisonous, while cream of tartar was natural and healthful.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] He attempted (and in Missouri briefly succeeded) in convincing legislators to ban aluminium compounds from use in baking powders.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] At the same time, he changed his own "Dr.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Price" baking powder to an aluminium-based formula that cornered two-thirds of the baking powder market in the southern states.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Eventually, after a number of legal and commercial battles that included bribery charges against Ziegler and a grand jury hearing, Royal lost the baking powder wars.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The idea that aluminium in baking powder is dangerous can be traced to Ziegler's attack advertising, and has little if any scientific support.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Aluminium is a commonly-found metal that appears in trace quantities in most foods.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] By the 1970s Royal had ceased to produce a cream of tartar baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] For those who wanted something similar, James Beard suggested combining two parts cream of tartar to one part baking soda just before using it, since the mixture would not keep.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Instead of cream of tartar, modern Royal baking powder contains a mixture of Hulman's sodium aluminium sulfate and Horsford's monocalcium phosphate.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] One more type of baking powder was introduced during World War II under the brand name Bakewell.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Faced with wartime shortages of cream of tartar and baking powder, Byron H.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Smith, a U.S. inventor in Bangor, Maine, created substitute products for American housewives.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Bakewell Cream was introduced as a replacement for cream of tartar.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] It contained sodium acid pyrophosphate and cornstarch and was labeled as a leavening agent.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] It could be substituted for cream of tartar or mixed with baking soda to replace baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Smith also sold a baking powder replacement, in which sodium acid pyrophosphate was already mixed with bicarbonate of soda and cornstarch.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Somewhat confusingly, it was marketed as "Bakewell Baking Powder" or "Bakewell Cream Baking Powder".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Some packaging uses the phrase "The Original Bakewell Cream".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] A product labelled "Bakewell Cream" may be either the cream of tartar substitute or the baking powder substitute depending on whether it is additionally identified as "Double acting" "Baking Powder".
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] A modern version containing acid sodium pyrophosphate, sodium bicarbonate and redried starch, is sold as being both aluminium-free and gluten-free.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Over time, most baking powder manufacturers have experimented with their products, combining or even replacing what were once key ingredients.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Information in the following table reflects the original ingredients as introduced by different individuals and companies.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The ingredients used may be very different from later formulations and current products.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Where an ingredient had multiple names, they are all listed together in the first occurrence, and the most common name listed thereafter.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The base for all these products is sodium bicarbonate, also known as baking soda.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The formation of a brand's current baking powder may be very different from the original formula they produced, shown above.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] They may now use combinations of acids, or different acids altogether.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] As of 2010, the two main baking powder companies in the United States were Clabber Girl and Calumet.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Calumet held about 1/3 of the American baking powder market, with Clabber Girl (which produces the Clabber Girl, Rumford, and Davis brands of baking powder, among others) dominating 2/3.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Generally, one teaspoon (5 g or 1/6 oz) of baking powder is used to raise a mixture of one cup (120 g or 4oz) of flour, one cup of liquid, and one egg.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Oetker's baking powder it is written that it contains 15 grams and is for use with 500 grams flour .
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] However, if the mixture is acidic, baking powder's additional acids remain unconsumed in the chemical reaction and often lend an unpleasant taste to food.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] High acidity can be caused by ingredients such as buttermilk, lemon juice, yogurt, citrus, or honey.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] When excessive acid is present, some of the baking powder should be replaced with baking soda.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] For example, one cup of flour, one egg, and one cup of buttermilk requires only 1⁄2 teaspoon of baking powder—the remaining leavening is caused by buttermilk acids reacting with 1⁄4 teaspoon of baking soda.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] However, with baking powders that contain sodium acid pyrophosphate, excess alkaline substances can sometimes deprotonate the acid in two steps instead of the one that normally occurs, resulting in an offensive bitter taste to baked goods.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Calcium compounds and aluminium compounds do not have that problem, though, since calcium compounds that deprotonate twice are insoluble and aluminium compounds do not deprotonate in that fashion.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Moisture and heat can cause baking powder to lose its effectiveness over time, and commercial varieties have a somewhat arbitrary expiration date printed on the container.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Regardless of the expiration date, the effectiveness can be tested by placing a teaspoon of the powder into a small container of hot water.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] If it bubbles vigorously, it is still active and usable.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Different brands of baking powder can perform quite differently in the oven.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Early baking powder companies published their own cookbooks, to promote their new products, to educate cooks about exactly how and when to use them, and because cooks could not easily adapt recipes that were developed using different types of baking powder.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Baking powders using cream-of-tartar, phosphates, or alums could behave very differently, and required different amounts for a desired rising effect.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In 2015, *Cook's Country*, an American TV show and magazine, evaluated six baking powders marketed to consumers.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In one test, six U.S. brands were used to bake white cake, cream biscuits, and chocolate cookies.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Depending on the brand, the thickness of the cakes varied by up to 20% (from 0.89 to 1.24 in).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] It was also found that the lower-rising products made what were judged to be better chocolate cookies.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Also, 30% of the testers (n=21) noted a metallic flavor in cream biscuits made with brands containing aluminium.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] As described above, baking powder is mainly just baking soda mixed with an acid.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] In principle, a number of kitchen acids may be combined with baking soda to simulate commercial baking powders.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Vinegar (dilute acetic acid), especially white vinegar, is also a common acidifier in baking; for example, many heirloom chocolate cake recipes call for a tablespoon or two of vinegar.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Where a recipe already uses buttermilk or yogurt, baking soda can be used without cream of tartar (or with less).
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] Alternatively, lemon juice can be substituted for some of the liquid in the recipe, to provide the required acidity to activate the baking soda.
[src:baking-powder/baking-powder] The main variable with the use of these kitchen acids is the rate of leavening.
